The XRD patterns of the CDs (Fig. 3
                           a) indicated a broad absorption peak between 20° and 50° with a 2θ value around 22° for E-CDs-175 °C, E-CDs-200 °C, and W-CDs-200 °C, suggesting that these CDs were semi-crystalline with large amorphous forms, consistent with previous studies (Chowdhury & Kumar, 2021; Cui et al., 2023). W-CDs-175 °C, however, exhibited no distinct diffraction peak, indicating that water at 175 °C was insufficient for the complete carbonization of SF residues into CDs. The zeta potential of the three CDs was measured at approximately -15.2 mV (Table 1
                           ), suggesting that the stability of the CDs was likely maintained through electrostatic repulsion between adjacent nanoparticles.
